Oct 29 2009 	Basic price Basic service	Our arrival set a negative tone that we struggled to forget. The website had stated that the hotel had carparking but when we got there this turned out to be incorrect. No car park, no valet service. There was a multi storey near by but this would have costed us more than the room itself!. The reception staff were lacking in knowledge and language skills. They kept on saying ' the hotel has no parking' to whatever car based question I posed, but were unable to offer any suggestions on how to solve this problem. Eventually we got to speak to someone more knowledgable who directed us to some free parking. It is worth saying that the directions were incorrect and that without sat-nav we would have been totally screwed. The parking was free but 10 minutes walk in blistering heat back to the hotel. From the moment we first arrived to actually getting to the room this whole debacle had taken an hour!The lack of local knowledge and language skills impacted us not long after. We asked if the metro was open and were told yes. We then asked if there was a station nearby and were told yes. We then asked for directions. The directions were poor and made no mention of there being no pavement and a large highway in the way that was virtually imposible to cross. When we got close to the station it was nowhere near being finished with large scale construction taking place. We could not believe that they had directed us to a closed metro station and were livid after struggling to get there in the heat.The reality is that this is a cheap hotel with nicer rooms than you could probably get elsewhere for the price. Yes the rooms are tiny but they were clean and everything worked. The location will be excellent once the metro is fully working as the WTC will have a station and even until then is central between old Dubai and new. I'm sure we would have loved our stay had we not have had the unfortunate start. If you remind yourself that you are paying a very basic price then you'll probably be pleasently surprised. 	
Oct 18 2009 	Inexpensive but for a reason	I stayed at the Ibis WTC in Dubai for four nights in October 2009. Arriving late (or early) at about 4AM in the morning, reception staff was able to welcome me by name, as there were basically no other guests arriving or around in the lobby. I visited Dubai mainly for sightseeing and to check, whether a longer second trip with friends would be worthwhile.LOCATIONThe hotel forms part of the convention centre and allows for direct access to the centre through the lobby. Sheikh Zayed Road stretches out behind a block of apartments (World Trade Centre Apartments, if you go to the front of the apartments, there is a small supermarket). The World Trade Centre Metro station will be within walking distance of the hotel once it is opened to the public. Right now, the Financial Centre station is the nearest operational one. Being somebody who rather walks some minutes instead of taking public transport or taxis, I had to change this behaviour in Dubai, as pedestrians seem not to be part of road planning. Speaking of taxis, there are not always taxis waiting outside the hotel, so one might bear that in mind. I did write down some costs for taxi rides (might vary, but for some reference):Airport (terminal 1) - Ibis: 37AEDIbis - Bur Dubai near Ministry of Finance: 25AEDIbis - The Address hotel (near Burj Dubai, Dubai Mall): 15AEDIbis - Emirates Towers: 10AED (minimum fare)Ibis - Jumeirah Beach Hotel: 37AEDFinancial Centre Metro station - trade centre (2mins from hotel): 10AED (minimum fare)HOTEL / ROOMSThe hotel looks quite new from the outside. However, the interior and the romms show some use and abuse. As mentioned above, staff was very friendly and helpful (especially at the reception). I had breakfast at the hotel once (55AED, buffett style), which I found to be enough for my eating habits. The standard food was avalable: scrambled eggs, sausages, choice of bread, rolls and toast, some pastries, cereals, joghurts and fruit. The drink section featured apple and orange juice, milk, choice of tea and choice of coffee-based beverages. The breakfast area is not too large and might get a bit crowded at some times. There was also a limited &quot;early bird&quot; breakfast available in the lobby for 25AED. I can't comment on the restaurant, as I did eat out in the evenings. A hint regarding water: There is a machine selling bottles (0,5l) of cold still water for only 1AED (coins required!) on every floor.The room (637 in my case) was large enough for one person, but seemed to be a regular double room for single use. Please refer to the pictures for more details on the general look. The regular TV set (I spotted Arabic, English, French and German channels) and telephone were all there, but e.g. no hairdryer or safe. The bathroom was quite small and showed some signs of usage. Towels were provided of course, but not regularly changed during my stay, even with one towel being really dirty upon arrival. This also was the major flaw of the hotel during my stay: the bathroom was not properly cleaned and the shower head had to be used quite carefully to not fully destroy its mount. Additionally, the shower basin did leak, requiring at least one towel on the floor to prevent flooding.VERDICTAll in all my stay at the Ibis WTC was not too bad considering the rate (399AED/night) and the fact that I did only stay in my room to sleep and shower. However, given the flaws regarding that last part, I might look for another hotel for my next stay in Dubai, probably one being located near Old Town / Burj Dubai for expanded dining opportunities. Travellers who have to stay within a tight budget might find the Ibis to suit their needs, if not expecting too much.	
Oct 18 2009 	Give it a miss - there are much better options in Dubai	The hotel is clean and easy to navigate. The rooms are small, and the bathroom is quite cramped, but usable. I found the beds to be moderately uncomfortable.My biggest gripe with this hotel is the service. While I wouldn't expect over the top service for a hotel in this price range, the front desk staff are rude and unhelpful, and appeared annoyed when asked the most benign questions. Unfortunately this held true for all four desk clerks with whom I interacted. In my student days I also worked as a hotel desk clerk, and I know what a challenge the job can be, but this was unacceptable. When asked (on a Friday) where a certain item might be purchased, we were advised to go to shops in a specific area of Dubai - however no mention was made that all shops are closed on Fridays - we took a cab there only to find that nothing would be open for 2 days. When asked about exchanging money, we were given misinformation and advised to utilize the hotel exchange at poorer rates. And when our travel plans were disrupted and we found ourselves needing to stay an extra day, our rate suddenly went up significantly. As this is their perogative and we didn't wish to traipse around locating additional lodging, we paid it, but it is poor customer service. And the breakfast originally included in our stay suddenly was no longer available. Internet service is about $30 USD for 24 hours and is relatively slow (although not the worst that we have run into in hotels in this region).The location is convenient if you have meetings at the World Trade Center, but otherwise the hotel is not particularly well located for a visitor - it is far from any amenities, leaving you at the mercy of the hotel restaurant (mediocre at best) and what little is offered in the hotel gift shop. If you are traveling for business and it's location suits you, then it is clean and inexpensive, and likely adequate. If you are traveling as a tourist, I would recommend finding something located in Deira for local atmosphere and convenience to the Souks and areas of Bur Dubai, or else somewhere along the coast for a more resort-feel.We stayed in another hotel in Deira for several days previously and found that to be much more convenient in location, as well as more service-oriented. Given the number of hotels in this town, I would advise anyone considering this hotel to look elsewhere.	
