Mar 25 2007 	Good value halfway between old and new cities	We arrived at 6am with room only booked for the next night. Helpful staff let us put our luggage in secure storage while we looked around the city. We returned at 10am and our room was ready (theoretically checkin is 12noon). Room was good although no view to speak of.Staff were helpful throughout our visit, and do note there are free shuttle buses to the 3 biggest malls (approx every 2 hours) as well as hourly shuttle buses to *and from* the airport.Ibis is about 10 minutes' taxi from the old city and the creek. Equally it's about 10 minutes' taxi from the new city, sites like the Burj Al Arab hotel and the &quot;Mall of the Emirates&quot; which contains Ski Dubai. All these timings are weekend timings, apparently things slow down a lot during weekday rush hours. You can also walk to the &quot;avenue&quot; of incredibly high rise buildings, takes about 10 minutes although they are rather soulless when you get there. Joggers can happily jog around the world trade centre block (Ibis, conference centre, Novotel) - we did, it takes about 15 minutes. However, there's not much else in the area unless you take a taxi; one passes the front door every couple of minutes.At £50 our room was good value. However, as budget travellers / backpackers, we may be tempted to stay in Bur Dubai (neer the creek) next time for closer proximity to the incredibly cheap Indian food in that area, and the souks. Business travellers or people with a reasonable budget will find it excellent value.	
Feb 10 2007 	A solid value	The Ibis Hotel at the World Trade Center in Dubai is probably one of the best value in Dubai. The Hotel is of a modern concept and clean. The guests are mostly business men attending trade fairs or transit guests looking for a clean and convenient accommodation for a couple of hours. The Ibis hotel is situated at the Exhibition Centre on Sheikh Zaid Road. There are traffic jams when people are going to work. The 10 Kilometer ride from the airport can take up to 45 minutes. There is not much around the hotel. Emirates Towers can be reached in 10 minutes by walk. Restaurants and shops at the Emirates Towers are expensive. There a couple of restaurants at the Ibis hotel or at the Novotel. The Novotel is situated at the other exit of the exhibition hall. Breakfast at the Ibis is very basic for AED 45.--. The better choice is the buffet at the Novotel for AED 70.— offering a wide selection of cold cuts incl. smoked salmon, Arabic fare, muesli, fruits and freshly cooked eggs. The hotel offers free transportation from the airport leaving every half an hour. A free shuttle bus service is also offered to City Centre (Deira), Mall of the Emirates (Shopping Centre with ski slope) and Mercato Market in Jumeira. The rooms are basic and clean; but pretty small. They have a large writing desk, big enough to work comfortably. Wifi service is payable. The bath rooms have only shower cabins. Little extras such as shampoo are provided by dispenser, if not empty as it was during my last stay. There is no swimming pool nor fitness facility at the hotel. The standard of the rooms is well above those seen in Ibis hotely in Europe. The Ibis is a good and solid value. Especially during winter months it is difficult to get a simliar standard at the same price in another hotel. The Ibis is often fully booked, it is therefore recommended to book early.	
